WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:16.840
There's no better place to have breakfast
than at the MoMA.

00:00:16.960 --> 00:00:17.960
We planned it ahead of time.

00:00:19.960 --> 00:00:20.960
Oh, this one's yours.

00:00:21.960 --> 00:00:22.880
How did I do that?

00:00:22.880 --> 00:00:23.980
This is just a go-to.

00:00:23.980 --> 00:00:25.920
You have to come here, you know?

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:30.320
You get refreshed, and get it all figured
out, then go on from there.

00:00:30.700 --> 00:00:36.360
You know until you walk in front of a piece
that suddenly grabs you, you know, you haven't

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:37.680
really experienced art.

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:39.220
I mean there's tons of work.

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:41.560
Not all pieces grab.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.080
But when you find that 1 out of 10, or 20,
or that one artist who you really connect

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:47.600
with, it's amazing.

00:00:57.940 --> 00:01:01.820
Sometimes when you get up in the morning,
you get up, you are thinking about so many

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:03.320
things that you wanna do.

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:10.160
And when you walk into Gallery 9, and you
look around you, you look at one side, it

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:11.160
looks dark.

00:01:11.740 --> 00:01:14.100
And you look at the middle, you see...you
know.

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:19.660
And I went back, I remember a couple of years
ago, I was looking into Monet.

00:01:19.660 --> 00:01:26.680
And I found out that that this painter actually
was dated back to the 20th century.

00:01:26.780 --> 00:01:29.440
I think it was 1899.

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:36.840
And then I think Monet died in 1926, if I
recall correctly.

00:01:36.860 --> 00:01:38.140
It's been a while.

00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:47.040
But look at it today, what was painted over
a century ago, we're still deriving pleasure,

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:48.880
happiness from it.

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:54.220
Sometimes when something bothers my mind,
when I walk to this gallery, sometimes I will

00:01:54.220 --> 00:01:57.580
just sit on one of the benches and I will
be looking.

00:01:57.580 --> 00:02:04.580
And if you look from one end to the other
end, you will see something different, and

00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:10.120
something that kind of console your mind,
something that makes you feel like, "You know what?

00:02:10.640 --> 00:02:13.260
This is kind of impressive."

00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:26.200
I like the impressionist, Van Gogh, Matisse.

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:30.140
I also like Klimt, but I asked and

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:34.520
they borrowed the masterpiece of Klimt that
they have here in MoMA.

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:37.660
So today I'm not going to see Klimt.

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:38.880
I'm upset.

00:02:39.020 --> 00:02:41.500
Well, next time.

00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:46.360
Well, I was studying a little bit of history
of art in my country, Peru.

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:56.860
So I have all my stuff here, and next, I like
Calder over there.

00:02:58.380 --> 00:03:01.480
I don't like so much but it's good.

00:03:01.480 --> 00:03:09.240
Perhaps there are masterpieces that you don't
like, but if they make you feel something,

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:10.900
it's okay.

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:17.260
Good afternoon, everyone.

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:19.100
Hi.

00:03:19.140 --> 00:03:24.020
