00:07:07.360 --> 00:07:09.300
So, hopefully this will go well.

00:07:09.400 --> 00:07:11.460
Thank you for coming.

00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:14.300
And we're gonna talk about this Franz Kline
painting, "Number 2," that he did.

00:07:14.300 --> 00:07:15.700
And why did I pick this painting?

00:07:15.820 --> 00:07:19.580
So for me, this was kind of the start of my
journey into art.

00:07:19.580 --> 00:07:23.820
In junior high, I took a school field trip
to the Cleveland Museum of Art, and I saw

00:07:23.820 --> 00:07:27.840
this painting there, not this painting, a
painting by Franz Kline there, and it was

00:07:27.840 --> 00:07:29.800
just unlike anything else I had ever seen.

00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:30.840
And I thought it was beautiful.

00:07:30.860 --> 00:07:33.820
It wasn't like a realistic painting.

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:37.680
It looked kind of like Japanese calligraphy.

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:41.360
And the color was different, the brushstrokes
were just so big and different.

00:07:41.360 --> 00:07:43.620
I was just captivated by it, and I thought
it was beautiful.

00:07:43.620 --> 00:07:45.800
I think I was about 16 or 17 at the time.

00:07:45.800 --> 00:07:49.400
Around that time at 17, I had a very, like,
life traumatic experience.

00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:51.060
I had this open heart surgery.

00:07:51.060 --> 00:07:52.660
It was, like, a big thing.

00:07:52.660 --> 00:07:55.340
And afterwards, I was just thinking about
it, and I told my dad, you know, I wanted

00:07:55.340 --> 00:07:58.360
to go back to the museum and see this painting.

00:07:58.700 --> 00:08:00.500
And I went there with him.

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:04.060
And I walked up to the painting, and I see
it, and I'm staring at it.

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:08.120
And there's this woman in a wheelchair next
to me, and the two of us were staring at this

00:08:08.120 --> 00:08:12.300
painting, and she just says to me, "It's very
powerful, isn't it?"

00:08:12.300 --> 00:08:17.620
And I felt like we were on the same page,
and we shared this moment, and it was just beautiful.

00:08:17.620 --> 00:08:21.200
And just looking at these paintings, they
kind of, like, draw you in.

00:08:21.200 --> 00:08:23.040
And I just fell in love with the work.

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:25.100
And then of course, my dad eventually made
his way there.

00:08:25.100 --> 00:08:28.260
And as I said, he's this mechanical engineer,
a very practical guy.

00:08:28.300 --> 00:08:30.060
And I'm like, "Hey, Dad, here's the painting."

00:08:30.060 --> 00:08:34.700
This is like this beautiful work of art, and
my dad of course goes, "No, not good.

00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:35.760
I don't like it."

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:40.200
And we, like, walk throughout the museum,
and we got to a painting of George Washington.

00:08:40.580 --> 00:08:42.080
And my dad goes, "See?

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:43.360
This is a good painting.

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:45.520
It looks just like George Washington."

00:08:45.540 --> 00:08:49.580
And because of that, it like made me like
this abstract expressionism even more.

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:50.900
The fact that my dad hated it, you know?

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:54.060
It's the kind of thing when you're a teenager,
you wanna rebel.

00:09:06.700 --> 00:09:10.180
The title is either "Black Widow" or "Spider."

00:09:10.260 --> 00:09:12.060
I think it was done in 1959.

00:09:13.420 --> 00:09:18.600
But just the concept is not actually that
abstract, like when you look at it, it's pretty

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:19.600
clear what it is.

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:22.560
I do wanna go kinda into it.

00:09:23.620 --> 00:09:25.160
Obviously, I'm not that tall.

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:29.620
I think people are like, if they don't know
enough, then they feel they shouldn't experience

00:09:29.740 --> 00:09:31.980
it or they won't experience it properly.

00:09:31.980 --> 00:09:34.120
And I think it's whatever you get from it.

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:37.660
And if you get a good experience and you wanna
go deeper, then you can go deeper.

00:09:37.680 --> 00:09:41.660
But I think that people can relate to it at
all different levels.

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:46.340
I may not be interpreting this right the way
the sculptor or whoever made it to be interpreted,

00:09:46.420 --> 00:09:49.880
but at the same time, I think he knows that
whoever will look at it can interpret it whatever

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:50.760
they want from it.

